    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1922-05-25T20:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1922-05-25T20:00:00-05:00" n="218"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d218">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">723.2515/945: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Peru</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Sterling</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Lima</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1922-05-25T20:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">May 25, 1922—8 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[Received 11 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>49. As reported in my 48, May 24, 2 p.m.,<note n="9" xml:id="d218fn9">Not
                        printed.</note> I had an interview yesterday with the President, and this
                    afternoon I saw the Minister of Foreign Affairs, who stated that it was decided
                    at a meeting of the Council of Ministers and of the Diplomatic Committee of the
                    Congress that the Government of Peru accepts the views of the Department of
                    State. The delegates to the conference will confine themselves to the
                    unfulfilled portions of the treaty and will not be instructed to present the
                    claim that the treaty has been nullified, but are to contend that article 3 has
                    been violated and cannot now be fulfilled. It would seem from our conversation
                    that the Minister expects disagreement with Chile over this article to
                    precipitate arbitration and that all claims that Chile has violated the treaty
                    will thereupon be brought up.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Sterling</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
